#212 Misc
    :date: 2024-12-09 18:25
    :shortdes: XY Problem
    :tags: Humor | Story | Tech

.The <a href="https://xyproblem.info">XY problem</a> is when you aren't sure
how to solve a problem, work on it yourself for a while, get stuck, and ask for
help, but instead of asking for help with your original problem, you ask for
help with one of your attempted <em>solutions</em>. This often turns out to be
a confusing waste of time, because the fact that you haven't managed to solve
the problem yet suggests there is something about it that you still don't fully
understand, and your attempted solution might be a complete dead end.

.One of my favorite examples occurred when I was working at the helpdesk at my
college. Someone came up to the desk and asked if I could teach him how to scan
a document from the campus copiers. Sure, no problem. We went to the nearest
copier and I walked him through putting the document in the feeder, logging in
to the copier, selecting the scan options, and choosing it to email it to
himself. He seemed to understand everything, and five minutes or so later he
had successfully sent the document to his campus email. Then:

<p>
<div><em>Him</em>: “Now, how can I print it?”</div>
<div><em>Me</em>: “You mean you want to…copy the document? From the copier?”</div>
</p>

.Needless to say, copying a document from the copier is a one-button-press
affair!


#211 Misc
    :date: 2024-12-04 23:30
    :shortdes: What percentage of people have ever been on an airplane?
    :tags: Travel | Statistics

.This is apparently a very hard question to answer. (I guess this makes sense –
the proportion will be totally different for every country because of both
geography and wealth, and surveying the whole world accurately is rather
difficult. Also, there's not a whole lot of reason to know except curiosity.)

.The closest thing to a consensus I could find was about 20% of the world
population, but on further investigation, this appears to trace back to a
random out-of-context quotation by the CEO of Boeing in 2017, and he actually
said “less than 20%” (he was discussing how Boeing still has a large potential
market). Claude quoted both “5–11%” and “20%” in the same response in pure LLM
mode, and 20% when it searched the web.

.The person who got me thinking about this claimed it was under 10%, and while
I didn't think this sounded all that far off, I was suspicious it might be out
of date, because of this hockey stick:

<img class="center" width="800px" loading="lazy" src="assets/images/global-flights.png">

<div class="callout">
<strong>Off topic:</strong> Can we all take a moment to appreciate how reliably the
graph of global passenger-flights momentarily plateaus every time there's a
recession in the USA? (Plus of course the literally world-stopping drop in
2020.)
</div>

.Gut check: if it's ~20%, that's an average of 2.8 flights per person who has
ever flown per year. But that's more like one round trip per year because this
is passenger-segments – if you take a round trip with one connection both ways,
that's 4 “flights”. Most routes need connections, but probably a
disproportionate volume of frequent flights are between hubs and can go direct,
so 1.4 flights in each direction on average seems maybe reasonable? Claude
thinks that's optimistic and says 60–70% of routes will need at least one
connection though, and that's not saying anything about international flights
or flights between remote places that need two or more connections. (I've never
needed more than two, but apparently you can <a
href="https://www.reddit.com/r/Flights/comments/193azxd/what_two_airports_require_the_most_transfers_to/?rdt=53874">find
airport pairs that require up to seven changes</a> if you work at it hard enough!) So
I'll guesstimate a number of 3.2 flights needed per round-trip on average. <1
flight per person per year seems like it might be too low, in which case a
smaller number of people must ever fly? But maybe averages are deceiving, let's
try some more detailed numbers – “ever flown” can mean you fly many times a
year, or you fly once in a decade or once in a lifetime, and there are probably
a lot of people in the lower groups.

.Another interesting constraint is that studies have found
<a href="https://partner.sciencenorway.no/climate-change-global-warming-transport/1-of-people-cause-half-of-global-aviation-emissions-most-people-in-fact-never-fly/1773607">1% of the world's population causes about 50% of global aviation emissions</a>
(the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pareto_principle">Pareto principle</a> strikes again).

.Here's an attempt to make the numbers work in a spreadsheet:

<img class="center" width="800px" loading="lazy" src="assets/images/flights-frequency-spreadsheet.png">

.Here I suppose that 50% of the people who have ever flown are “very occasional
fliers,” taking a trip by air only a handful of times in their lifetime (about
once a decade). Another 30% fly once every two years on a vacation. Another 15%
live far away from their family or occasionally fly on business, three times
per year on average. And the last 5% (this is actually the 1% quoted above,
divided by the fraction of people we're claiming have ever flown, so it's
elastic and if you change that fraction it will change this and move the
“regular fliers” notch to make 100%) take 10 trips a year on average. (Of
course, some take a lot more, but quite a few people up in this range will take
just a few.)

.That only gets us to 43% of global flights taken by 1% of the population, but
some chunk of these people will often fly first-class or even private, which is
far more carbon-intensive, so I'd bet this ends up being somewhere in the
neighborhood of 50% of <em>emissions</em>. And presumably 50% isn't the exact
number!

.That gets us to around 4.8 billion; 2024 flights are projected to be about 4.9
billion. Interestingly, if we try decreasing the fraction of people in the
world who have ever flown, the number of total flights per year actually has to
go <em>up</em>, because this implies that the fraction of frequent fliers who
are in the top 1% of the whole world's population must increase, which makes me
think 20% is significantly more plausible than 10%; if anything, my estimate of
the number of flights taken by frequent fliers every year seems low, and
raising it would further exacerbate this effect.

.So all this seems maybe about plausible for 20%?
But I made a lot of assumptions, and mostly don't expect them to be super accurate.
Here's the <a href="https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1M1gMtbfJvxBeVg8PQ_4OQVgLc0JLDWyflJRiqrnKFtk/edit?usp=sharing">spreadsheet</a>
if you want to try your own.
Let me know if you learn something interesting!


#210 Misc
    :date: 2024-11-24 12:00
    :shortdes: You don't have to be cynical about America
    :tags: Society

.The liberal side of American politics has recently shied away from displays of patriotism,
or sometimes even claims that America has any redeeming qualities.
I know people who don't like celebrating Independence Day.
And look – it's reasonable to be disillusioned.
There's a lot to dislike, both in our past and in our present.

.But I think Americans who have become cynical about their country
are spending too much time looking at an absolute scale of how good they can possibly imagine a country being,
instead of a comparison with other actual options.
Yes, this country's history includes, among other things,
racism, slavery, genocide, war crimes, broken promises to entire peoples, hypocrisy, kleptocracy,
pissing contests between leaders that ruin millions of ordinary people's lives, propaganda, and toxic ideologies.
For that matter, many of these are still alive and well today, and all of them are still rooted.
But have you ever tried finding a country that has avoided all, or even most, of those?
Not so easy.

.Certainly, that others also do the wrong thing does not mean you have no responsibility for doing it.
But I think it does illuminate the obvious fact that humans are human and countries are made up of humans,
and so always doing the right thing is impossible.
Giving up on someone because they haven't always done the right thing
is as unreasonable as giving up on them because they haven't learned how to fly yet.
Criticize, sure.
Educate yourself on the failures to inform where you go next, absolutely.
Give up and hate where you live because of events you had no part in? Nah, I'll pass.

.Indeed, accepting imperfection is part of the mythos of America.
We are the land of believing anything can be improved and pursuing ridiculous, impossible dreams –
and always falling short of the dreams.
Yet the better parts of America's history are nothing if not proof that that's a useful exercise;
it still drives change even when you don't make it all the way.
When you inevitably come up short, it's easy to stare ahead at how far short you are and grimace,
but once in a while you ought to also twist your head around and <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=88XRwBiUGSk">look at how far you've come</a>.
Sometimes it's truly awe-inspiring when you finally do.

.Of course we should keep striving to improve; the status quo is not good enough.
But it's much easier to improve something from a place of love,
    when you aren't trying to find someone to blame,
    when you don't feel guilty about things that aren't your fault,
    when you hope to take something you care deeply for and leave it even better than you found it.
When you start from a place of disillusionment and hate,
    you're more inclined to focus on how bad the world is <a href="https://mosmu.se/#FramePositively">than on how you can make it better</a>,
    improvements seem utterly out of step with the magnitude of the problem,
    and you'll probably give up and leave or spend your time petitioning the Adults In Charge to fix everything.

.Spoiler alert: there are no Adults In Charge. It's up to you.
<a href="https://hyperboleandahalf.blogspot.com">Allie Brosh</a>:

<img class="center" width="400px" loading="lazy" src="assets/images/somebody-should-do-something.jpg">

.If you dislike America enough that you're looking for a new home,
then I'll let you harbor that dislike.
But if you, like most of us, think your country is your worst option except for all the other ones out there,
I'd like to suggest you might be better off making peace with it.

.As we come closer to political instability and autocracy than we have since the Civil War
and the country faces stagnation and some very serious structural problems,
I think this is more important than ever.
Believe there's something worth preserving and we're on a hero's journey towards something a little bit better every step of the way,
and the snags don't seem so unmanageable.
Maybe it's irrational, but that's OK. It gets results.


#209 Misc
    :date: 2024-11-24 09:55
    :shortdes: Talking to LLMs is a rare instance where speech-to-text is better
    :tags: AI | Design | Tech

.This is about how fast I type on a typical day:

<img class="center" width="500px" loading="lazy" src="assets/images/typing-speed.png">

.(It was chilly in my office and my fingers were stiff when I did this run; I'd
probably do 5 to 10 words per minute better otherwise.)

.I can certainly still talk faster than I can type, but a natural
conversational pace is probably only about a third faster. Even more
importantly, it's a great deal harder to edit when you're talking, and when I
write I seldom write the entire thing and then go back and edit; I try parts of
each sentence a few times as I work to figure out what I want to say. That
means I find speech-to-text virtually useless for writing – it makes it much
harder to think and doesn't even speed me up much if everything goes perfectly.
And extended writing is the <em>best</em> case for speech-to-text when using a
computer; when the chunks of text you're entering are smaller, the comparative
speed difference is less meaningful and the amount of fiddly editing you can
expect to have to do is even greater.

.When I want to ask Claude or ChatGPT a question, though, the situation is
usually reversed. For one-off interactive use, its performance is no worse if
my input text has typos, corrections, and suboptimal phrasings in it. Typing
out my question feels like quite a lot of work, especially compared to a web
search where I can get away with just a few words. Worse, typing puts me in a
mode of thinking where I try to find the best possible way to phrase what I'm
saying, which is a complete waste of time – in the unlikely event Claude
misunderstands what I meant because I chose my words poorly, I can just clarify
and ask it to try again. And nobody is ever going to see my query after the
conversation is done.

.If you haven't started speaking many of your LLM queries yet, give it a try!


#208 Misc
    :date: 2024-11-23 09:10
    :shortdes: You can live resize partitions?!
    :tags: Tech

.I keep running out of space on my /home partition on my Linux desktop and
having to carefully move files onto my file server, clear caches, and so on (of
course, the used space usually reaches 100% at the most inconvenient possible
time). I realized at some point that I'd left about 180 GB of unallocated space
at the end of the disk, so I figured I'd extend the /home partition into part
of that space.

.Having grown up in an era when it was impossible to even change the size of a
partition with OS tools, and you'd have to delete it and recreate it (backing
up and restoring your data in the process), I'd been putting this off for
months, thinking I'd have to remind myself how to boot into the rescue
environment to resize the partition, and that sounded pretty annoying.

.But I was absolutely astounded to discover today that nowadays (at least on
disks with a GPT partition table on a recent Linux) you can <em>resize a
partition that's currently mounted and in use</em>, while the OS is running,
without even interrupting disk access requests. I was able to just open
<code>gparted</code>, turn off swap since a swap partition was in the way,
delete the swap partition, extend the /home partition, and recreate the swap
partition (this time at the far end of the disk so I wouldn't even have to do
that again). It took about 90 seconds.

.Nobody's ever going to win much recognition for improving partition table
management, but this goes well with Adam Mastroianni's recent essay “<a
href="https://www.experimental-history.com/p/underrated-ways-to-change-the-world">Underrated
ways to change the world</a>” – this silly little innovation will save people
hundreds of thousands of hours of annoying tasks over the course of the coming
decades.


